(57, 1, 10, 48, 4, 19, 19, 'my son Onesimus', 'Spiritual Birth and Formation', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual rebirth and growth. Both passages emphasize the process of nurturing and forming believers in faith, with Onesimus being a ''son'' in faith and the ''little children'' in Galatians representing those in spiritual development.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(57, 1, 10, 54, 1, 2, 2, 'my son', 'Father-Son Relationship in Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual fatherhood, as both Paul refers to Onesimus as ''my son'' and Timothy as ''my own son in the faith.'' Both passages emphasize the bond formed through faith and mentorship.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(57, 1, 10, 10, 19, 37, 38, 'my son Onesimus', 'Connection of Servanthood and Legacy', 'This connection highlights the theme of servanthood and the desire for legacy. In Philemon, Onesimus is referred to as a ''son'' in the context of servitude, while in 2 Samuel, Chimham is presented as a servant seeking to honor his family legacy.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(57, 1, 10, 56, 1, 4, 4, 'my son', 'Spiritual Fatherhood in Paul’s Letters', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual fatherhood, as both passages refer to individuals described as ''sons'' in a spiritual sense. Paul refers to Onesimus as ''my son'' and to Titus as ''mine own son,'' emphasizing their close relationships.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(57, 1, 10, 10, 9, 1, 7, NULL, 'Kindness and Restoration', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of showing kindness to those in need. In Philemon, Paul seeks to restore Onesimus, while David extends kindness to Mephibosheth for Jonathan''s sake.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(57, 1, 11, 55, 4, 11, 11, 'profitable to thee and to me', 'Profitability in Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being ''profitable'' in ministry. In Philemon, Onesimus is described as becoming profitable, while in 2 Timothy, Mark is noted for his profitability to Paul.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(57, 1, 11, 18, 30, 1, 2, 'unprofitable, but now profitable', 'Profit and Worthlessness Theme', 'This connection highlights the contrast between past unprofitability and current value. Both passages emphasize the idea of worth and usefulness, with Philemon reflecting on Onesimus''s transformation and Job lamenting the lack of profit from those he once deemed unworthy.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(57, 1, 11, 42, 15, 32, 32, 'profitable to thee and to me', 'Transformation from Unprofitability to Life', 'This connection highlights the theme of transformation, where Onesimus is described as becoming ''profitable'' after being ''unprofitable,'' paralleling the brother in Luke who was ''dead'' and is now ''alive again.'' Both passages emphasize the joy and value found in redemption and restoration.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(57, 1, 11, 60, 2, 10, 10, 'unprofitable, but now profitable', 'Transformation from Unprofitability to Profitability', 'Both passages emphasize a transformation from a state of unworthiness to one of value and belonging. Philemon speaks of Onesimus becoming profitable, while 1 Peter describes a shift from not being a people to becoming the people of God.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(57, 1, 11, 40, 25, 30, 30, 'unprofitable', 'Contrast of Profitability', 'This connection highlights the contrast between being ''unprofitable'' and ''profitable.'' Philemon 1:11 speaks of a servant who has become profitable, while Matthew 25:30 warns against the fate of an unprofitable servant.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(57, 1, 11, 42, 17, 10, 10, 'unprofitable', 'Servanthood and Profitability', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being unprofitable in service. In Philemon, Onesimus is described as previously unprofitable, while in Luke, servants acknowledge their unprofitability after fulfilling their duties.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(57, 1, 11, 45, 3, 12, 12, 'unprofitable', 'Connection of Profitability', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being unprofitable and then becoming profitable. In Philemon, Onesimus transitions from being unprofitable to profitable, while Romans describes all as having become unprofitable.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
